# pyframe â€” .env.example
#
# Copy this file to `.env` in the project root and adjust values for your
# environment. Values are read at startup via Pydantic Settings with the
# `PYFRAME_` prefix (see `main.py`).
#
# Notes
# - Lines starting with `#` are comments.
# - On Windows paths, you can use either double backslashes (e.g. C:\\Users\\you\\Pictures)
#   or single forward slashes (e.g. C:/Users/you/Pictures).
# - On Linux/macOS, use normal POSIX paths (e.g. /home/you/Pictures).
# - Enum values are case-insensitive in practice (they are upper-cased by a validator).
# - If a value is invalid, the application will print a validation error and exit.
#
# Required
# --------
# Directory to scan for images (recursively). Must exist.
# Example (Windows):
# PYFRAME_IMAGE_DIRECTORY=C:\\Users\\you\\Pictures
# Example (Linux/macOS):
# PYFRAME_IMAGE_DIRECTORY=/home/you/Pictures
#
# Uncomment ONE of the following and set it to your actual images folder:
# PYFRAME_IMAGE_DIRECTORY=C:\\Users\\you\\Pictures
# PYFRAME_IMAGE_DIRECTORY=/home/you/Pictures


# Optional
# --------
# How to fill background borders when image/screen aspect ratios differ.
# Accepted values:
#   BLACK | WHITE | TOP_PIXEL | SIDE_PIXEL | CLOSEST_BW
# Default: CLOSEST_BW
# PYFRAME_FILL_TYPE=CLOSEST_BW

# Slideshow order mode.
# Accepted values:
#   SEQUENTIAL | RANDOM
# Default: RANDOM
# PYFRAME_SLIDESHOW_MODE=RANDOM

# Cross-fade transition duration in seconds.
# Default: 2
# PYFRAME_TRANSITION_DURATION=2

# Seconds to show each image before auto-advancing (when not paused).
# Default: 10
# PYFRAME_SLIDESHOW_DELAY=10


# Platform-specific
# -----------------
# Linux/X11 only: If DISPLAY is unset, the app will try DISPLAY=:0 automatically.
# You generally do not need to set this, but you can override explicitly if needed:
# DISPLAY=:0
